<div id="review_2172941956" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2172941956" />
    <a title="Logan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28038482-logan"><img alt="Logan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1573222858p2/28038482.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2172941956?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Logan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Logan" href="/user/show/28038482-logan">Logan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2172941956" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12629359686844172076">Mixed feelings on this one. If I didn&apos;t know any better I might have said that this was one of L&apos;Amour&apos;s earliest books. But it wasn&apos;t. It just felt a bit unpolished and lacking in any kind of finesse. I&apos;ve read a lot about L&apos;Amour&apos;s own personal experiences and how he thought a Western man should be portrayed, and this character is exactly that: though oddly told by the character himself in the first person. Bendigo Shafter is 6&apos;2&quot;, kind and gentle toward women, a hard worker who takes satisfac</span>
  <span id="freeText12629359686844172076" style="display:none">Mixed feelings on this one. If I didn't know any better I might have said that this was one of L'Amour's earliest books. But it wasn't. It just felt a bit unpolished and lacking in any kind of finesse. I've read a lot about L'Amour's own personal experiences and how he thought a Western man should be portrayed, and this character is exactly that: though oddly told by the character himself in the first person. Bendigo Shafter is 6'2", kind and gentle toward women, a hard worker who takes satisfaction in his labour, who understands the Indian and respects him, who reads Blackstone's Law (and Plutarch etc.), and is a fast, sure shot but never brags about it or gets into a fight if he can avoid it.<br /><br />Sounds great, yet for me it was lacking that true craftsmanship that would make this a work of art. Enjoyable, just not brilliant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12629359686844172076" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


