<div id="review_1607970216" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1607970216" />
    <a title="Allison" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21995463-allison"><img alt="Allison" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1455489578p2/21995463.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1607970216?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Allison" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Allison" href="/user/show/21995463-allison">Allison</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1607970216" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7389791474595347884">This book was deep on philosophy but light on plot. I tend to like my books to be just the opposite, however I did find that some of the quotes really spoke to me. In between the great quotes, though, it felt like each turning point in Bendigo&apos;s life was its own vignette and by the end it just didn&apos;t feel like they added up to a cohesive whole.<br/>I felt like Bendigo was a really great guy, maybe too great? What&apos;s the male equivalent of a &quot;Mary Sue&quot;? A &quot;Gary Stu&quot; or a &quot;golden boy&quot; perhaps? Yeah, tha</span>
  <span id="freeText7389791474595347884" style="display:none">This book was deep on philosophy but light on plot. I tend to like my books to be just the opposite, however I did find that some of the quotes really spoke to me. In between the great quotes, though, it felt like each turning point in Bendigo's life was its own vignette and by the end it just didn't feel like they added up to a cohesive whole.<br />I felt like Bendigo was a really great guy, maybe too great? What's the male equivalent of a "Mary Sue"? A "Gary Stu" or a "golden boy" perhaps? Yeah, that was Bendigo.<br />All in all, it was not bad for my first and, so far, only Louis L'Amour.<br /><br />Read for the 2016 Reading Challenge prompt "A National Book Award Winner".</span>
  <a data-text-id="7389791474595347884" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


