  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2537342104" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2537342104" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2763719-john"><img alt="John" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1638938390p2/2763719.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2537342104?book_show_action=true">Sep 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/2763719-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780553123548" href="/book/show/121096.Bendigo_Shafter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2763719-john?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2763719-john?shelf=western">western</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2537342104" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11008596759403862762">Though by no means L&apos;Amour&apos;s first great novel (Heck, HONDO came out in 1953, though admittedly it was a glorified movie tie-in), BENDIGO SHAFTER is certainly a milestone in his particular oeuvre. At double or triple the length of his usual novels, it is a near-epic that, while not exactly a magnum opus, does feel like a genuine attempt at one.<br/>Some novels give off the impression that the author wished to regurgitate a lifetime&apos;s worth of knowledge and experience in the space of a single volume, </span>
  <span id="freeText11008596759403862762" style="display:none">Though by no means L'Amour's first great novel (Heck, HONDO came out in 1953, though admittedly it was a glorified movie tie-in), BENDIGO SHAFTER is certainly a milestone in his particular oeuvre. At double or triple the length of his usual novels, it is a near-epic that, while not exactly a magnum opus, does feel like a genuine attempt at one.<br />Some novels give off the impression that the author wished to regurgitate a lifetime's worth of knowledge and experience in the space of a single volume, whether it be Stephen King's THE STAND, Any Rand's ATLAS SHRUGGED, or Herman Melville's MOBY DICK. To a lesser extent, BENDIGO SHAFTER is much the same way, with L'Amour making a strong case for why he remains the bestselling Western author of all time.<br />Unlike most L'Amour novels, which sorta peter out as they go along, BENDIGO SHAFTER remains consistently great in its entirety, though certain aspects are relatively clumsy in relation to the level of storytelling craft otherwise on display. Another draft, and perhaps this would be a modern LAST OF THE MOHICANS, but unfortunately L'Amour was never big on the revision process, and boy does it show. Like when Bendigo tells us a lion attack kept him bedridden for two whole weeks, then a few pages later we see him go horseback riding a mere week after said attack. Or the fact that Chapter 32 ends with the line "'When I go,' I decided suddenly, 'I'll take Lorna with me," and Chapter 33 ends with nearly the exact same line: "When I go east I am taking Lorna with me." Call me crazy, but I think ending two chapters in a row with the very same line is odd, to say the least, and I'm pretty sure L'Amour just forgot that he'd used that line already. A good editor should probably catch stuff like that, but it doesn't change the fact that L'Amour released two other full-length novels the same year as BENDIGO SHAFTER (1979), and that's a tremendous output for anyone not named James Patterson. When you crank out books that fast, it's no surprise that certain inconsistencies get overlooked.<br />Believability is occasionally a minor issue, as well. Bendigo is just too awesome a human being to make for a believable teenager--even one forged in a crucible of hard work and hardship. Bendigo is a crack shot, an outstanding builder, an expert survivalist and hunter, a level-headed thinker, and an all-around fighting man. He goes from building houses to driving cattle across the country to serving as town marshal to striking gold to becoming a published writer in prestigious newspapers to finally turning his hand toward ranching. He constantly saves people's lives and never fails to outdraw--and outsmart--the bad guys. With this much going for him, there's no room for him to experience much in the way of character growth. There are passages that indicate L'Amour intended this novel as a bildungsroman; in that one aspect, I'd say he failed.<br />BENDIGO SHAFTER tells a sprawling story, one that feels both typical and atypical for L'Amour. Atypical, because of its loose plot structure and wide range of strongly defined characters. Typical, because he can't help but insert gratuitous action scenes whenever possible, even when the book would work better without them. Probably, he figured his audience wouldn't go for a novel that didn't have tons of gunplay to offset the more realistic and mundane aspects of frontier life. The book often seems embarrassed by its own quality and occasionally works to convince you that, at heart, it's just a boys' adventure novel.<br />But I don't buy it. BENDIGO SHAFTER is the rare Western that is so good, even non-Western fans will enjoy it. And long-time readers of L'Amour will get an especial kick out of seeing one of the Sacketts play a plum supporting role.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11008596759403862762" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

