    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2086795297" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2086795297" />
    <a title="Oleta Blaylock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2805345-oleta-blaylock"><img alt="Oleta Blaylock" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1254689016p2/2805345.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2086795297?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Oleta Blaylock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Oleta Blaylock" href="/user/show/2805345-oleta-blaylock">Oleta Blaylock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Leather Bound 9780553062700" href="/book/show/121072.Bendigo_Shafter">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2086795297" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10490456099650461203">This is another one of Louis L&apos;Amour&apos;s epic novels. The book covers a number of years as a group of people try to build a community while dealing with the difficulties of frontier life in the mountains. It is also a story of the journey of one man to educate himself and find a place in the world where he can make a difference. This story also has a good deal written about Ethan Sackett. There is only one mention of Ethan Sackett before this book and that was in RIDE THE RIVER. If this is the sam</span>
  <span id="freeText10490456099650461203" style="display:none">This is another one of Louis L'Amour's epic novels. The book covers a number of years as a group of people try to build a community while dealing with the difficulties of frontier life in the mountains. It is also a story of the journey of one man to educate himself and find a place in the world where he can make a difference. This story also has a good deal written about Ethan Sackett. There is only one mention of Ethan Sackett before this book and that was in RIDE THE RIVER. If this is the same Ethan then he is still alive during the same time as Tell, Orrin and Tyerel come West, as well as all the other youngsters in the Sackett clan.<br /><br />Bendigo Sackett comes west like so many others to find land and a place to build a place for himself and his family. He also realizes that he is uneducated and must find a way to solve that problem. One of the people in the wagon train that he was a part of is a widow and she takes him under her wing. She has brought a chest of books West with her and she loans them out to Bendigo. The books open up a whole new world for him. He is soon getting newspapers from several large cities and trading books with people that he meets on his various adventures. Books were a rare thing in West especially when every ounce of weight on a wagon was need for the necessities of living. As Bendigo's world expands he begins to question what he should do with his life.<br /><br />I really enjoyed this book. As usual Louis L'Amour brings the richness of the areas he writes about into a story of human discovery. These stories make you want to go find these places and explore them. To try and imagine what life must have been like for theses people. While I love all his books these longer books seem to be so much richer and enthralling. So much history has been lost to time and the lack of people that know how to write. What could we have learn from the plains indians if they had had a written history, if there knowledge of healing and nature had been written down. The same is true for the earlier settlers and explorers. Few of them left diaries of what they found and how they survived. If time travel were possible this is one of those places and times I would love to visit. Not to participate but to observe and record. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10490456099650461203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


